===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|abacus}}, {{m|la|abax}}; from Ancient Greek {{m|grc|ἄβαξ||board covered with sand}}, possibly from {{etyl|he|en}} {{m|he|אבק||dust|tr=āvāq}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.ə.kəs/|/əˈbæk.əs/|lang=en}}, rarely {{IPA|/əˈbɑk.əs/|lang=en}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.ə.kəs/|/əˈbæk.əs/|lang=en}}, rarely {{IPA|/əˈbɑk.əs/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abacus.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|abaci|abacuses}}

# {{label|en|obsolete}} A table or tray [[strewn]] with sand, anciently used for drawing, [[calculating]], etc. {{defdate|Attested from around 1350 (1387) until around 1470.}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>
# A calculating table or frame; an instrument for performing [[arithmetical]] [[calculations]] by balls [[sliding]] on wires, or [[counters]] in grooves, the lowest line representing units, the second line, tens, etc. {{defdate|First attested in the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref>
#: {{ux|en|I've heard merchants still use an '''abacus''' for adding things up in China.}}
# {{label|en|architecture}} The [[uppermost]] portion of the [[capital]] of a [[column]], immediately under the [[architrave]]. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# A board, tray, or table, divided into [[perforated]] [[compartments]], for holding cups, bottles, or the like; a kind of [[cupboard]], [[buffet]], or [[sideboard]]. {{defdate|First attested in the late 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

