==Latin==

===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|la|abax}}

===Etymology===
From {{der|la|grc|ἄβαξ||board}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{la-IPA|abacus}}

===Noun===
{{la-noun|abacus||abacī|m|second}}

# a [[square]] [[board]]
# [[sideboard]]
#* {{Q|la|Cicero|In Verrem|II|4|35|quote=Ab hoc '''abaci''' vasa omnia, ut exposita fuerunt, abstulit.|trans=From this place he removed all the '''sideboard's''' dishes, since they had been exposed.}}
# [[counting board]].
#* {{Q|la|Persius|Saturae|I|131|quote=...nec qui '''abaco''' numeros et secto in pulvere metas / scit risisse vafer, multum gaudere paratus, / si cynico barbam petulans nonaria vellat.|trans=...nor the man who has the wit to laugh at the figures on the '''counting board''' and the cones drawn in sand, ready to go off in ecstasies if a prostitute pulls a Cynic by the beard.}}
# [[gaming board]].
#* {{Q|la|Suetonius|De vita Caesarum|Neronis|XXII|1|quote=Sed cum inter initia imperii eburneis quadrigis cotidie in '''abaco''' luderet, ad omnis etiam minimos circenses e secessu commeabat, primo clam, deinde propalam, ut nemini dubium esset eo die utique affuturum.|trans=But in the early stages of his rule he used to play every day on a '''gaming board''' with ivory chariots. He would also travel from his retreat to the Circus games, even the least important ones, at first in secret and then openly. As a result, no one was in any doubt that he would be present in Rome that day at least.}}
# a painted ceiling or wall [[panel]].
#* {{Q|la|Pliny the Elder|Naturalis Historia|XXXIII|56|quote=Hoc autem et Attico ad lumina utuntur, ad '''abacos''' non nisi marmoroso, quoniam marmor in eo resistit amaritudini calcis.|trans=This and the Attic sort they used for high lights, for '''panels''' none but the marmorean kind, because the marble in it resists acridity of the lime.}}

